summary.para:
The Objective-C declaration is :

            struct objc_class
            {
            struct objc_class* isa;
            struct objc_class* super_class;
            const char* name;
            long version;
            long info;
            long instance_size;
            struct objc_ivar_list* ivars;
            struct objc_method_list** methodLists;
            struct objc_cache* cache;
            struct objc_protocol_list* protocols;
            };

The Objective-C declaration is :

            typedef struct objc_ivar *Ivar;
            struct objc_ivar
            {
            char* ivar_name;
            char* ivar_type;
            int ivar_offset;
            };

The Objective-C declaration is :

            struct objc_ivar_list
            {
            int ivar_count;
            struct objc_ivar ivar_list[1];
            };

The Objective-C declaration is :

            struct objc_method
            {
            SEL method_name;
            char * method_types;
            IMP method_imp;
            };

The Objective-C declaration is :

            struct objc_method_list
            {
            struct objc_method_list *obsolete;
            int method_count;
            struct objc_method method_list[1];
            }

The Objective-C declaration is :

            struct objc_protocol_list
            {
            struct objc_protocol_list *next;
            int count;
            Protocol *list[1];
            };

An Objective-C method is simply a C function that take at least two argumentsself and _cmd. For example, given the following function:

            void myMethodIMP(id self, SEL _cmd)
            {
            // implementation ....
            }

            you can dynamically add it to a class as a method (called resolveThisMethodDynamically) like this:

            class_addMethod([self class], @selector(resolveThisMethodDynamically), (IMP) myMethodIMP, "v@:");

The Objective-C declaration is :

            struct objc_super
            {
            id receiver;
            Class class;
            };

example.para:
The type MyOwnType1 will be registered with the "MyOwnType1" name.

            [ObjectiveCClass]
            public class MyOwnType1 : NSObject
            {
            ...
            }

The type MyOwnType2 will be registered with the "Type2" name.

            [ObjectiveCClass("Type2")]
            public class MyOwnType2 : NSObject
            {
            ...
            }

summary.para:
Here are some examples of result: MethodCorresponding selector
public void DoThis()DoThis
public void DoThis(int value)DoThisWithValue:
public void DoThis(NSString str, int val)DoThisWithStr:val:

Here are some examples of result: ConstructorCorresponding selector
public TestClass()Init
public TestClass(int value)InitWithValue:
public TestClass(NSString str, int val)InitWithStr:Val:

